{"term":"1972","caseName":"Tonasket v. Washington","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1972/71-1031","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 12, 1972","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16881","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Pirtle, you may proceed.","start":0,"stop":3.146,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3.146,"stop":5.41,"duration":2.26},{"text":"I’m Robert Pirtle, attorney for the appellant in this case.","start":5.41,"stop":8.819,"duration":3.41},{"text":"This case comes to Court on appeal from the Supreme Court of the State of Washington.","start":8.819,"stop":13.199,"duration":4.38},{"text":"Part of the jurisdiction was noted on June 12, 1972.","start":13.199,"stop":17.28,"duration":4.08},{"text":"The facts in this case are relatively simple although complicated somewhat by later enacted legislation both by the State of Washington, the Colville Confederated Tribes and by later activities of the State and the appellant and the tribes and the Federal Government.","start":17.28,"stop":34.837,"duration":17.56},{"text":"We’ll begin here with the thorough recognition that Washington is Public Law 83-280 State.","start":34.837,"stop":40.99,"duration":6.15},{"text":"That is pursuant to that Act, it has taken jurisdiction, certain jurisdiction over Indians and Indian reservations.","start":40.99,"stop":50.313,"duration":9.32},{"text":"The reservation here is the Colville reservation in Eastern Washington comprising some 1.3 million acres.","start":50.313,"stop":57.032,"duration":6.72},{"text":"It is governed by a 14-member tribal council under a Constitution of by-laws approved by the Federal Government.","start":57.032,"stop":65.534,"duration":8.5},{"text":"Leonard Tonasket, the appellant here is a full-blood Indian.","start":65.534,"stop":69.067,"duration":3.53},{"text":"He is a direct descendant of Chief Tonasket of the Okanogan Band.","start":69.067,"stop":75.092,"duration":6.03},{"text":"In 1964, he borrowed some $6,000 of federally restricted funds with which to build a store on his trust allotment inside the reservation.","start":75.092,"stop":85.45,"duration":10.36},{"text":"That land was specifically approved by the Federal Government.","start":85.45,"stop":89.404,"duration":3.95},{"text":"He made and additional loan of $800 to with which to purchase cigarette inventory.","start":89.404,"stop":95.273,"duration":5.87},{"text":"That loan was also a federally restricted funds again approved by the Federal Government.","start":95.273,"stop":101.773,"duration":6.5},{"text":"He operated his store selling cigarettes and sundries and Indian artifacts and clothing as a trader on the reservation but without a federal trader’s license.","start":101.773,"stop":112.622,"duration":10.85},{"text":"He did not collect tax for the State of Washington nor for the tribe at that time.","start":112.622,"stop":118.031,"duration":5.41},{"text":"The State of Washington arrested him in 1967 and seized his cigarette inventory leaving the rest of his inventory intact.","start":118.031,"stop":127.041,"duration":9.01},{"text":"He then began this action inequity seeking a declaratory judgment as to his rights to make sales in the reservation on his trust land.","start":127.041,"stop":135.87,"duration":8.83}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this case involved in a claim by the State of Washington only of the power to collect the taxes on sales to non-Indians or does it involve the claim generally on all sales?","start":135.87,"stop":150.28,"duration":14.41},{"text":"I couldn’t -- I wasn’t sure of that after reading the brief.","start":150.28,"stop":154.175,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"I can clarify that for you, Your Honor.","start":154.175,"stop":156.331,"duration":2.16},{"text":"The State Supreme Court ruled that Public Law 83-280 specifically granted the State complete jurisdiction over Indian trading with no exceptions.","start":156.331,"stop":165.45,"duration":9.12},{"text":"Now, the State of Washington in its briefs in this case is willing to concede that the State has no jurisdiction over trade with respect to Indians.","start":165.45,"stop":173.735,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s what I understood to say.","start":173.735,"stop":175.264,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"But that’s not what the decision says.","start":175.264,"stop":177.252,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that’s what caused my confusion.","start":177.252,"stop":178.929,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"I can understand that, Your Honor.","start":178.929,"stop":180.454,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose buying a carton of cigarettes, an Indian selling a carton to another Indian is commerce within the Indian tribe, isn’t it?","start":180.454,"stop":190.581,"duration":10.13}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"It is.","start":190.581,"stop":190.98,"duration":0.4},{"text":"That’s clearly Indian commerce within the federal constitutional definition, Your Honor.","start":190.98,"stop":196.344,"duration":5.36},{"text":"We contend that sales from the Indian to the non-Indian on the reservation also come within that definition.","start":196.344,"stop":202.655,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Washington’s Sales Tax Law like that of most other States and that the tax is being -- is regard as being imposed on the seller and that he can pass it along to the buyer if he wants to but incidence of the tax is on him.","start":202.655,"stop":217.02,"duration":14.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"True.","start":217.02,"stop":217.564,"duration":0.54},{"text":"It is, Your Honor.","start":217.564,"stop":220.333,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Part of the attorney’s question about the applicability of 280 in Washington having been raised in the state courts?","start":220.333,"stop":228.986,"duration":8.65},{"text":"I asked this because one of the amicus briefs suggested that it was not.","start":228.986,"stop":233.01,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I did not try this case in the Superior Court, so I’m somewhat at a disadvantage in that respect.","start":233.01,"stop":239.634,"duration":6.62},{"text":"I can assure you that I would’ve raised the question.","start":239.634,"stop":241.849,"duration":2.22},{"text":"It was not raised in the Superior Court nor argued in the Supreme Court.","start":241.849,"stop":245.571,"duration":3.72},{"text":"But it is a viable question as pointed out in that brief and it will be raised in the future.","start":245.571,"stop":251.253,"duration":5.68},{"text":"The Court would want to consider it.","start":251.253,"stop":252.718,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Supreme Court of Washington was this argument made as a distinction between the two kinds of sales or was it just an all-or-nothing?","start":252.718,"stop":267.248,"duration":14.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I believe the argument was made with respect to the two kinds of sales but the Supreme Court decided to go all the way.","start":267.248,"stop":274.839,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"But then do I understand you come here without the 280 suggestion having been made below.","start":274.839,"stop":281.805,"duration":6.97},{"text":"I take it that you are conceding this.","start":281.805,"stop":284.282,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"That 280 is in fact effective in the State, Your Honor?","start":284.282,"stop":287.891,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"That it was raised in the state courts, the applicability of 280.","start":287.891,"stop":293.859,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we have to distinguish in a very fine way here.","start":293.859,"stop":297.425,"duration":3.57},{"text":"I understood the previous question to mean is Public Law 83-280 actually legally approved in the State of Washington.","start":297.425,"stop":304.399,"duration":6.97},{"text":"That is has the State legally accepted jurisdiction?","start":304.399,"stop":307.192,"duration":2.79},{"text":"That is the contention that was not raised below.","start":307.192,"stop":309.935,"duration":2.74},{"text":"It was not briefed for the State Supreme Court and which will be raised in the later case.","start":309.935,"stop":315.085,"duration":5.15},{"text":"The other part of the question or as I understand it, the question you’re asking now is, how about the application of Public Law 83-280 to the facts of this case?","start":315.085,"stop":324.105,"duration":9.02},{"text":"That was raised in expense of the argument.","start":324.105,"stop":324.626,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m asking if that issue was raised in the state courts.","start":324.626,"stop":326.788,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"It was Your Honor.","start":326.788,"stop":327.522,"duration":0.73},{"text":"Yes.","start":327.522,"stop":328.017,"duration":0.5},{"text":"And extensively argued.","start":328.017,"stop":329.134,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, one of the amicus briefs as I read it takes the other position, do I misread it?","start":329.134,"stop":335.297,"duration":6.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the amicus brief for the National Congress of American-Indians says, “There is a substantial question as to whether the State of Washington has complied with the federal requirements and assuming jurisdiction pursuant to Public Law 83-280 and the Court should recognize that fact in the consideration of this case.","start":335.297,"stop":350.911,"duration":15.61}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But that issue was not raised below?","start":350.911,"stop":352.349,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not and the Court may wish to remand it for the raising and briefing of that issue, Your Honor, especially from the Osburn, say, especially in the light of the new legislative history concerning Public Law 83-280 which has just been uncovered in the archives.","start":352.349,"stop":365.397,"duration":13.05}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But everybody, trying the case in the Washington courts, in effect agreed and conceded that Washington had validly complied with the terms of that law.","start":365.397,"stop":375.463,"duration":10.07}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would not say it was conceded, Your Honor.","start":375.463,"stop":377.33,"duration":1.87},{"text":"It was not raised by the attorney representing the appellant below and I was not in the position to raise it in the Appellate Court as appellant counsel.","start":377.33,"stop":386.486,"duration":9.16}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Today, in the proceeding on the premise around the hypothesis that 280 is in effect in the State of Washington, is it?","start":386.486,"stop":393.234,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":393.234,"stop":394.358,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s my understanding.","start":394.358,"stop":395.082,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not conceding that but I’m --","start":395.082,"stop":395.963,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, you’re conceding on the hypothesis --","start":395.963,"stop":397.28,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of necessity in that position.","start":397.28,"stop":399.421,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or the arguendo.","start":399.421,"stop":400.226,"duration":0.81},{"text":"That’s just you’re making the assumption that it is without conceding anything.","start":400.226,"stop":404.597,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"True.","start":404.597,"stop":405.803,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Now, after this action was begun, the legislative activity which I referred to occurred.","start":405.803,"stop":412.08,"duration":6.28},{"text":"Washington passed a new Act concerning the regulation of cigarettes in 1972.","start":412.08,"stop":417.211,"duration":5.13},{"text":"That Act specifically authorized any citizen of the State of Washington to buy, possess and use two cartons of tax-free cigarettes without incurring tax liability. --","start":417.211,"stop":431.972,"duration":14.76},{"text":"Excuse me?","start":431.972,"stop":432.679,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Two cartons per year?","start":432.679,"stop":434.131,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Two cartons per person at any one given time.","start":434.131,"stop":437.176,"duration":3.05},{"text":"That is a possession matter.","start":437.176,"stop":438.869,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You could go day after day and --","start":438.869,"stop":441.214,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"True.","start":441.214,"stop":442.142,"duration":0.93},{"text":"And the Oregon tax is 4 cents which is 13 cents less in Washington.","start":442.142,"stop":447.528,"duration":5.39},{"text":"The Idaho tax is 7 cents which is 10 cents less and many, many State residents have been going back and forth across the borders bringing cigarettes in.","start":447.528,"stop":456.019,"duration":8.49},{"text":"That was the reason for the Act in 1972.","start":456.019,"stop":459.655,"duration":3.64},{"text":"Towns were being searched and the housewives of the important people on the State were very angry.","start":459.655,"stop":464.724,"duration":5.07},{"text":"Although, that’s outside the record but it’s well-known in the State of Washington.","start":464.724,"stop":469.076,"duration":4.35},{"text":"Now, after the Act which Governor Evans characterized as legitimatizing Indian sales to the extent of two cartons, the Colville Confederated Tribes enacted the Colville Tobacco Ordinance which makes the handling and sale of all cigarette products on the reservation a tribal enterprise.","start":469.076,"stop":487.245,"duration":18.17},{"text":"It requires that the outlets be licensed by the tribe.","start":487.245,"stop":490.654,"duration":3.41},{"text":"It requires that the operator have a license from the tribe, that the operation be conducted on trust land, that the operator have a federal trader’s license.","start":490.654,"stop":500.499,"duration":9.85},{"text":"It levies a tribal tax on every pack of cigarette sold on the reservation.","start":500.499,"stop":506.21,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it now.","start":506.21,"stop":509.123,"duration":2.91},{"text":"The appellant or petitioner here does have a federal trader’s license at this point?","start":509.123,"stop":512.424,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"He does, Your Honor.","start":512.424,"stop":513.268,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though the record may not show that.","start":513.268,"stop":515.506,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"The record, it’s in the appendix.","start":515.506,"stop":518.837,"duration":3.33},{"text":"It was not in the case below but of course, it occurred after the facts of this case happened.","start":518.837,"stop":523.765,"duration":4.93},{"text":"He has a license from the tribe and from the Federal Government as a licensed trader.","start":523.765,"stop":529.181,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Has it moot this Court?","start":529.181,"stop":531.544,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it has not, Your Honor.","start":531.544,"stop":532.604,"duration":1.06},{"text":"It’s still on his trust land in East Omak which is an Indian village.","start":532.604,"stop":536.127,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"So, the trust land is equal to the (Inaudible)?","start":536.127,"stop":539.108,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"It is.","start":539.108,"stop":539.582,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":539.582,"stop":541.414,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":541.414,"stop":541.902,"duration":0.49},{"text":"It’s a trust allotment under the General Allotment Act.","start":541.902,"stop":545.97,"duration":4.07},{"text":"Now, the law which applies to this case is rather not preempting but the central issue emerges very clearly.","start":545.97,"stop":551.417,"duration":5.45},{"text":"That is, does Public Law 83-280 constitute a grant of tax jurisdiction to the State?","start":551.417,"stop":557.503,"duration":6.09},{"text":"The State Supreme Court says, “Yes, it constitutes a plenary grant of jurisdiction over Indians with only the exception set forth in 2 (b) and 4 (b) of the Act.","start":557.503,"stop":567.676,"duration":10.17},{"text":"The Court went further.","start":567.676,"stop":568.986,"duration":1.31},{"text":"It said it constitutes a complete grant to the State of Indian trading jurisdiction.","start":568.986,"stop":574.846,"duration":5.86},{"text":"Now, I would ask the Court to examine the Act.","start":574.846,"stop":577.941,"duration":3.1},{"text":"Putting in context, in 1953, Congress was considering a number of major cases of Indian legislation following four or five separate categories.","start":577.941,"stop":587.852,"duration":9.91},{"text":"Public Law 83-280 was merely one piece.","start":587.852,"stop":590.793,"duration":2.94},{"text":"It had a narrow legislative purpose.","start":590.793,"stop":593.379,"duration":2.59},{"text":"It was a law and order statute.","start":593.379,"stop":596.21,"duration":2.83},{"text":"It was specifically for the purpose fulfilling the hiatus in law-enforcement on the reservation from the criminal standpoint.","start":596.21,"stop":605.205,"duration":9},{"text":"It was for the purpose of providing a state form for the determination of civil litigation from the civil standpoint.","start":605.205,"stop":614.225,"duration":9.02},{"text":"And if you examine the Act, the language of the Act from page A-10 of brief, you’ll notice that it says that the jurisdiction given to the State is jurisdiction over civil causes of action and it provides that civil laws of the State that are of general applicability to private persons or private property shall have the same effect on Indian reservations.","start":614.225,"stop":638.975,"duration":24.75},{"text":"Now, the Court has to ask itself, is that language of plenary grant a jurisdiction?","start":638.975,"stop":645.122,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Consider it was respect to taxation.","start":645.122,"stop":649.374,"duration":4.25},{"text":"It says nothing about taxation but when Congress wants state taxes to apply on an Indian reservation, it says so in no uncertain terms.","start":649.374,"stop":659.085,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Look at the Claim of Termination Act on page 27 of the brief.","start":659.085,"stop":663.227,"duration":4.14},{"text":"It provides that after termination, the property shall be subject to the same taxes, state and federal, as in the case of non-Indians.","start":663.227,"stop":671.914,"duration":8.69},{"text":"Look at Menominee Termination Bill on page 30, provides that all statutes of the United States which affect Indians because of their status as Indians shall no longer be applicable and it provides that the laws of the State shall apply to the tribe and its members.","start":671.914,"stop":687.871,"duration":15.96},{"text":"That is plenary jurisdiction grant language.","start":687.871,"stop":693.064,"duration":5.19},{"text":"Now, Congress has made one general act with respect to state taxes on Indian reservations, that’s Buck Act which you’ve heard referred to in the other cases today.","start":693.064,"stop":702.142,"duration":9.08},{"text":"Congress said, “States, you may apply your taxes in federal reservations both income, use, sales but you may not apply them to Indian reservations.”","start":702.142,"stop":714.904,"duration":12.76},{"text":"That has never changed.","start":714.904,"stop":716.932,"duration":2.03},{"text":"Frost versus Wenie says, “Acts of Congress will not be deemed repealed by implication.”","start":716.932,"stop":723.759,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Just you said about that, said you may apply your taxes when --","start":723.759,"stop":727.186,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"To federal reservations but not Indian reservations.","start":727.186,"stop":730.293,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":730.293,"stop":731.293,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"And that’s 4 U.S.C. 109.","start":731.293,"stop":734.259,"duration":2.97},{"text":"Now, when Congress wants state tax to apply on an Indian reservation, it says it.","start":734.259,"stop":740.035,"duration":5.78},{"text":"It says it with the expressed language.","start":740.035,"stop":742.451,"duration":2.42},{"text":"It provided in 25 U.S.C. Section 398 that minimal interest could be taxed.","start":742.451,"stop":748.756,"duration":6.3},{"text":"It provided in the Brown Stevens Bill, Public Law 291, 49 Statute 65 that taxation could apply with respect to one state.","start":748.756,"stop":760.128,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Congress knew what it was doing when it passed Public Law 83-280 and it said, “Now, we’re going to repeal certain statutes.","start":760.128,"stop":767.319,"duration":7.19},{"text":"We’re going to repeal 18 U.S.C. Section 1152.”","start":767.319,"stop":770.832,"duration":3.51},{"text":"That is the Act that applies the Federal Criminal Code on Reservations.","start":770.832,"stop":774.381,"duration":3.55},{"text":"It repealed it.","start":774.381,"stop":776.05,"duration":1.67},{"text":"Congress said, “We’re going to repeal 18 U.S.C. Section 1153.","start":776.05,"stop":780.603,"duration":4.55},{"text":"That is the Ten Major Crimes Act.","start":780.603,"stop":783.361,"duration":2.76},{"text":"But very significantly, Your Honors, Congress did not say, “We’re going to repeal the Traders Act.”","start":783.361,"stop":789.016,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Congress did not say, “We’re going to repeal the Buck Act.”","start":789.016,"stop":792.547,"duration":3.53},{"text":"Congress knew what it was repealing and what it was not repealing.","start":792.547,"stop":797.129,"duration":4.58},{"text":"If you look at the legislative history and especially the hearing which the Federal Government just find on archives, the hearing of the subcommittee of June 29, 1953, you’ll find the tax discussion concerning this Bill.","start":797.129,"stop":810.592,"duration":13.46},{"text":"The first one and I’m delighted to have found it because in that, Mr. Soloway who was chief counsel for the BIA discusses the question of subsidy to the States assuming jurisdiction under this Act and the Congressmen involved are Congressmen from all of the States with large Indian populations and they repeatedly say, “but what about the federal subsidy?","start":810.592,"stop":831.019,"duration":20.43},{"text":"Who will pay for the burden on the Court system?","start":831.019,"stop":833.433,"duration":2.41},{"text":"What about this jurisdiction, this additional law and order, cost to the States?”","start":833.433,"stop":837.484,"duration":4.05},{"text":"And Mr. Soloway says, “The Government feels that this is just a burden the States have got to assume if they wanted.”","start":837.484,"stop":843.806,"duration":6.32},{"text":"And you all know the history of the Act.","start":843.806,"stop":845.954,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Some States refused to assume that burden because they would not have any tax money to pay for it with.","start":845.954,"stop":852.547,"duration":6.59},{"text":"This is the point in the dialogue at which Congress if it had ever intended it would have said, “Congressmen, you may now have your States tax the Indians.","start":852.547,"stop":862.39,"duration":9.84},{"text":"Arizona, you can tax those 100,000 Navajos and pay for this jurisdiction if you assume it.","start":862.39,"stop":868.669,"duration":6.28},{"text":"Washington, you may tax those 26,000 Indians and you may pay for this jurisdiction if you assume it.”","start":868.669,"stop":874.592,"duration":5.92},{"text":"Congress didn’t.","start":874.592,"stop":876.193,"duration":1.6},{"text":"Congress left the Buck Act intact.","start":876.193,"stop":878.489,"duration":2.3},{"text":"It left the Trader Statute intact.","start":878.489,"stop":880.898,"duration":2.41},{"text":"It made no reference to the Taxation and Public Law 83-280 in terms of the specific grant that Congress’ Policy dictates.","start":880.898,"stop":890.057,"duration":9.16},{"text":"Now, if the Court were to uphold the State Supreme Court in this case, the consequences would be disastrous.","start":890.057,"stop":896.518,"duration":6.46},{"text":"It would mean an impel of all of the tax immunities of Indian tribes which this Court has said is not likely to be attributed to Congress than the Lone Wolf and Hitchcock case.","start":896.518,"stop":907.425,"duration":10.91},{"text":"It would be the rejection of the expressed language requirement which this Court required in the Squire versus Capoeman case.","start":907.425,"stop":914.539,"duration":7.11},{"text":"It would be an implied repeal of the Buck Act.","start":914.539,"stop":917.476,"duration":2.94},{"text":"It would be a rejection of your policy in Frost versus Wenie that federal statutes are not replied -- repealed by implication.","start":917.476,"stop":924.875,"duration":7.4},{"text":"It would be a repeal by implication of Trader Act.","start":924.875,"stop":929.636,"duration":4.76},{"text":"It would be a rejection of firm congressional policy that when Congress wants to repeal one of its statutes, it says so.","start":929.636,"stop":937.525,"duration":7.89},{"text":"And--","start":937.525,"stop":937.708,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m just curious Mr. Pirtle, this is why a committee hearing so recent as 1953 should be locked up in the archives and available only by special permission.","start":937.708,"stop":947.99,"duration":10.28}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it was unpublished and one of those difficult situations in which I learned to Matthew Grant too late, almost, that you can only get those unpublished committee reports and typed up from the transcripts if you get special permission from the Committee itself and the Government did that in this case because it’s urgent that this Court see that there was a discussion concerning subsidy to the States.","start":947.99,"stop":971.854,"duration":23.86},{"text":"And that discussion made it clear that Congress never even considered in committee for a minute imposing any tax liability on the Indian people themselves.","start":971.854,"stop":980.428,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Now, congressional policy in 1953 said, “We want to fulfill this hiatus in law enforcement.","start":980.428,"stop":986.053,"duration":5.63},{"text":"We want States to be able to take jurisdiction.”","start":986.053,"stop":988.593,"duration":2.54},{"text":"In 1968, that policy is still intact except with consent of the Indian people.","start":988.593,"stop":994.947,"duration":6.35},{"text":"If there were a tax affreightment here, if there were a tax imposition, no Indian tribe in America would ever consent to any jurisdiction no matter how much it was lacking in law enforcement.","start":994.947,"stop":1006.634,"duration":11.69}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But that was if the States might have a comparable reaction if they are deprived of tax revenues, isn’t that possible?","start":1006.634,"stop":1014.135,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"The States neither were not getting any additional tax revenue, Your Honor and many of them refused to take jurisdiction just for that reason.","start":1014.135,"stop":1020.149,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Pirtle, doesn’t your -- the argument you draw from the congressional policy that you’re mentioned depends were very large part on the notion that in 1953, the Congressmen from States with large Indian population would have viewed taxes on Indians as being a very lucrative source of revenue and declined to mention it or failed to come forward with it?","start":1020.149,"stop":1044.651,"duration":24.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1044.651,"stop":1045.136,"duration":0.48},{"text":"You should read that language specifically.","start":1045.136,"stop":1047.791,"duration":2.65},{"text":"It’s in my reply brief which is the red one and in there they say, “Well, wait a minute, Mr. Soloway.","start":1047.791,"stop":1053.487,"duration":5.7},{"text":"If you’re going give jurisdiction to the States, these Indian people are not taxed, are they?”","start":1053.487,"stop":1057.298,"duration":3.81},{"text":"And he said, “Well, they pay certain taxes as off the reservation they pay taxes.”","start":1057.298,"stop":1060.558,"duration":3.26},{"text":"But he said, “But their land is not taxed, and they don’t pay income tax, and their corporations on the reservation don’t pay tax, do they?","start":1060.558,"stop":1066.877,"duration":6.32},{"text":"So, who’s going to pay for this?”","start":1066.877,"stop":1068.833,"duration":1.96},{"text":"That was the general tenor of the conversations.","start":1068.833,"stop":1070.788,"duration":1.95},{"text":"All of the Congressmen recognized there was no tax to be forthcoming from the Indian people.","start":1070.788,"stop":1075.413,"duration":4.63},{"text":"And they demanded that Congress subsidized it in some way and Congress decided not to.","start":1075.413,"stop":1079.715,"duration":4.3},{"text":"In North Dakota, in fact passed a statute saying, we take jurisdiction as soon as the BIA makes provision for a reimbursing this for the cost and it was held that that could not be done.","start":1079.715,"stop":1090.573,"duration":10.86},{"text":"I think I better save my last few minutes for rebuttal, Your Honor.","start":1090.573,"stop":1095.556,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":1095.556,"stop":1096.489,"duration":0.93},{"text":"Mr. Ziontz.","start":1096.489,"stop":1102.974,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Alvin J. Ziontz","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1102.974,"stop":1106.46,"duration":3.49},{"text":"This is a tax case but we see it in a larger context.","start":1106.46,"stop":1111.398,"duration":4.94},{"text":"We see the case and I say, we are speaking as counsel for the Colville Confederated Tribes and amicus tribes as a case involving essential aspects of Indian tribal sovereignty.","start":1111.398,"stop":1124.501,"duration":13.1},{"text":"A concept which we think is long overdue for revitalization by this Court.","start":1124.501,"stop":1130.515,"duration":6.01},{"text":"And I would point out certain basic principles that I think in here, in this case.","start":1130.515,"stop":1135.376,"duration":4.86},{"text":"First, I think it’s necessary to start with the principle that Indian tribes are sui generis because of the special aspects of their position and I would point out five special aspects that apply here.","start":1135.376,"stop":1147.358,"duration":11.98},{"text":"We deal with a group of people, first of all, of specific ancestry with a special historic relationship to the United States and a relationship which involves a national honor.","start":1147.358,"stop":1159.196,"duration":11.84},{"text":"Secondly, the people occupy their own land area, an area with established boundaries reserved from non-Indian encroachment.","start":1159.196,"stop":1167.625,"duration":8.43},{"text":"This was the basic purpose of the United States in establishing that reservation and guaranteed to the Indians by the United States, a guarantee given before creation of State Government and looking towards the future encirclement of the reservation by State Government.","start":1167.625,"stop":1185.552,"duration":17.93},{"text":"Thirdly, the lands and the income from the lands are held in trust by the United States.","start":1185.552,"stop":1192.067,"duration":6.52},{"text":"A very significant legal factor because it is the foundation for the fiduciary relationship.","start":1192.067,"stop":1199.013,"duration":6.95},{"text":"That is to say the United States is trustee of lands for its Indian beneficiaries.","start":1199.013,"stop":1205.561,"duration":6.55},{"text":"This does not necessarily depend on any guardian ward principle.","start":1205.561,"stop":1210.303,"duration":4.74},{"text":"Fourth, a tribal government functioning over that territory according to a tribal constitution which was submitted to the United States and given approval by the United States.","start":1210.303,"stop":1222.004,"duration":11.7},{"text":"And finally, the land, the people and their Government are all subject to the plenary power of Congress and all under the tutelage of the United States.","start":1222.004,"stop":1231.798,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Now, given these factors which are present here and I think distinguished away the Oklahoma cases and (Inaudible).","start":1231.798,"stop":1241.469,"duration":9.67},{"text":"We have clearly in tribal sovereignty aspect.","start":1241.469,"stop":1244.966,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Tribal sovereignty does not derive from Congress.","start":1244.966,"stop":1247.66,"duration":2.69},{"text":"Congress did not grant the tribes their inherent power of self-government.","start":1247.66,"stop":1252.373,"duration":4.71},{"text":"Congress may restrict it.","start":1252.373,"stop":1253.88,"duration":1.51},{"text":"Congress may destroy it but unless Congress has done so, that sovereignty prevails.","start":1253.88,"stop":1259.841,"duration":5.96},{"text":"An essential element of that sovereignty is taxing power.","start":1259.841,"stop":1263.717,"duration":3.88},{"text":"The federal policy towards these tribal governments is undeniable.","start":1263.717,"stop":1267.57,"duration":3.85},{"text":"It is the strength of them.","start":1267.57,"stop":1268.768,"duration":1.2},{"text":"It is to preserve them, its institutions.","start":1268.768,"stop":1271.435,"duration":2.67},{"text":"Congress has reached the decision that this is a way for progress to be achieved for the Indian people.","start":1271.435,"stop":1277.544,"duration":6.11},{"text":"The Indian people have accepted that in issue.","start":1277.544,"stop":1280.95,"duration":3.41},{"text":"They responded to it.","start":1280.95,"stop":1282.091,"duration":1.14},{"text":"They were vitally involved in the affairs of their tribe.","start":1282.091,"stop":1285.679,"duration":3.59},{"text":"Educated Indians are participating in their tribal government.","start":1285.679,"stop":1289.291,"duration":3.61},{"text":"Indians who have served in the military, come back to the reservations and have run for office and are participating in tribal affairs.","start":1289.291,"stop":1295.814,"duration":6.52},{"text":"This is a viable, important concept which should not be glossed over in the concern between Congress and the States.","start":1295.814,"stop":1304.016,"duration":8.2},{"text":"Now, State of Washington here, although it argues that Public Law 280 give jurisdiction of taxes tribe, insists that even without 280, it has some kind of residual jurisdiction that it could’ve imposed this tax and in fact does impose the cigarette tax over all tribes in the State of Washington, quite apart from 280.","start":1304.016,"stop":1325.667,"duration":21.65},{"text":"Now, there are identified at least six basic principles in the cases that bar the State, bar any state from imposing any State taxes on a tribe which meets all these qualifications.","start":1325.667,"stop":1338.387,"duration":12.72},{"text":"There is, I say first of all, the concept of tribal sovereignty.","start":1338.387,"stop":1342.396,"duration":4.01},{"text":"Secondly, in the case of the Colville tribes, tribal preemption, the tribe has, subsequent to the arrest of Mr. Tonasket, passed its own statute.","start":1342.396,"stop":1352.913,"duration":10.52},{"text":"That statute is entitled to recognition.","start":1352.913,"stop":1355.213,"duration":2.3},{"text":"In State ex rel.","start":1355.213,"stop":1356.099,"duration":0.89},{"text":"Turtle versus Merrill, the Ninth Circuit recognized that a tribe which validly legislates, preempts the field and a state may not impair that legislation.","start":1356.099,"stop":1366.858,"duration":10.76},{"text":"And it should be noted that Washington law provides and the Attorney General has interpreted the law to mean that wherever the State has jurisdiction, it is exclusive.","start":1366.858,"stop":1375.304,"duration":8.45},{"text":"There is no concurrent tribal jurisdiction.","start":1375.304,"stop":1377.393,"duration":2.09},{"text":"It ousts the tribal jurisdiction entirely and particularly in the field of excise tax.","start":1377.393,"stop":1382.205,"duration":4.81},{"text":"If Washington state law applies in toto, then there is not an integrum left for tribal law.","start":1382.205,"stop":1389.898,"duration":7.69},{"text":"A third bar to the extension of the state taxes is the so-called infringement test and I suggest that one deserves careful attention because surely there should be some guidelines about what as to what kind of factual showing needs to be made at the trial level before the Court can conclude that there is or is not infringement.","start":1389.898,"stop":1409.794,"duration":19.9},{"text":"This should not be a judicial obstruction.","start":1409.794,"stop":1413.672,"duration":3.88},{"text":"Fourth is the Doctrine of Federal Instrumentality.","start":1413.672,"stop":1415.922,"duration":2.25},{"text":"I wouldn’t elaborate on that.","start":1415.922,"stop":1417.547,"duration":1.63},{"text":"That’s a familiar doctrine.","start":1417.547,"stop":1418.747,"duration":1.2},{"text":"Fifth is the Doctrine of Federal Preemption and the trader statute has been held to be a federal preemption of Indian commerce.","start":1418.747,"stop":1425.117,"duration":6.37},{"text":"And finally is the Doctrine of Federal Policy.","start":1425.117,"stop":1427.805,"duration":2.69},{"text":"State laws cannot invade an area which is contrary to or impedes a congressional policy.","start":1427.805,"stop":1434.883,"duration":7.08},{"text":"280 has been urged by the State as giving it cart blanche to assert this tax liability on the Indians of the Colville reservation.","start":1434.883,"stop":1444.914,"duration":10.03},{"text":"I submit that 280 does not assist the State in its position.","start":1444.914,"stop":1449.237,"duration":4.32},{"text":"280 clearly reserves out from state jurisdiction, the traditional tax immunity of Indians.","start":1449.237,"stop":1457.629,"duration":8.39},{"text":"I submit the exclusion statute, exclusion section, must be read as preserving all prior law.","start":1457.629,"stop":1464.726,"duration":7.1},{"text":"See Kirkwood versus Arenas which held to that effect.","start":1464.726,"stop":1469.45,"duration":4.72},{"text":"In summary, I would say that the Court in 1953, Congress was attempting to achieve several inconsistent goals and the lack of hearings perhaps attest to the fact that a statute was not drawn with the care that it should’ve been drawn with.","start":1469.45,"stop":1485.172,"duration":15.72},{"text":"On the one hand, it wanted to replace the jurisdictional tangle with the uniform system of state law and on the other hand, it also wanted to preserve Indian tribes on their territorial base.","start":1485.172,"stop":1496.265,"duration":11.09},{"text":"A careful examination of the statute shows an unmistakable congressional attempt to keep the State out of areas involving the use of trust property.","start":1496.265,"stop":1505.831,"duration":9.57},{"text":"There’s clearly no more direct example of use of trust property than an Indian conducting a grocery store on his allotment on the reservation.","start":1505.831,"stop":1517.33,"duration":11.5},{"text":"The federal policy looks towards Indians developing their lands in non-agricultural, non-natural resource ways, in getting into business.","start":1517.33,"stop":1526.329,"duration":9},{"text":"I believe that on behalf of the tribes, this Court deserves to -- the doctrine of tribal sovereignty deserves careful examination.","start":1526.329,"stop":1535.589,"duration":9.26},{"text":"It is a third factor in this three-way fight between the tribes, the Federal Government and the States.","start":1535.589,"stop":1541.14,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1541.14,"stop":1541.988,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you gentlemen.","start":1541.988,"stop":1542.863,"duration":0.88},{"text":"We’ll resume in the morning.","start":1542.863,"stop":1546.446,"duration":3.58}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 13, 1972","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16961","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll resume arguments in 71-1031, you may proceed.","start":0,"stop":16.027,"duration":16.03}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":16.027,"stop":20.49,"duration":4.46},{"text":"This case involves the first assertion in this Court that an individual Indian citizen may engage in a private commercial venture literally, any private commercial venture in direct competition with other citizens of the state or for that matter even with other Indians so unfortunate as to have been declared competent or to have moved off the reservation with paying or collecting any of the excise taxes applicable to all such businesses on an equal basis conducted by other citizens of the state.","start":20.49,"stop":65.434,"duration":44.94},{"text":"It involves a claim of a right literally to destroy those other competing businesses, a claim, which is asserted again by a citizen entitled by the Constitution to every right and privilege extended by the state to every other citizen.","start":65.434,"stop":86.507,"duration":21.07},{"text":"The factual setting and which this claim arrives is this.","start":86.507,"stop":91.277,"duration":4.77},{"text":"The Colville Reservation is not an isolated track in the State of Washington occupied only by Indians.","start":91.277,"stop":99.936,"duration":8.66},{"text":"Nor for that matter are the amicus reservations.","start":99.936,"stop":105.405,"duration":5.47},{"text":"They lie close Tacoma, to Olympia, to Seattle and the various other major metropolitan areas of the State of Washington.","start":105.405,"stop":118.498,"duration":13.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, those are the amicus, but where is the Colville?","start":118.498,"stop":120.587,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"The Colville is this very large one here.","start":120.587,"stop":123.645,"duration":3.06},{"text":"The amicus are here, here, here and here.","start":123.645,"stop":128.887,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Any big cities near the Colville.","start":128.887,"stop":131.217,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"I am getting to the city, which is partly on the Colville reservation right now.","start":131.217,"stop":139.684,"duration":8.47},{"text":"The Colville reservation under the 1970 census figures has 1,779 Indian inhabitants and 2,429 or 58% non-Indian inhabitants on the reservation.","start":139.684,"stop":157.368,"duration":17.68},{"text":"This is a BIA map, the upper right hand corner shows the entire reservation, which is in yellow on the other map.","start":157.368,"stop":164.137,"duration":6.77},{"text":"This section is the Northwest corner of the map.","start":164.137,"stop":169.419,"duration":5.28},{"text":"The city of Omak, Washington incidentally both our briefs and the other briefs are in error in speaking of the city called East Omak.","start":169.419,"stop":179.119,"duration":9.7},{"text":"There is simply in Washington a City of Omak, Washington, which lies on both sides of the Okanogan River, which is the boundary of the Colville reservation and roughly this portion of the reservation is inside the City of Omak.","start":179.119,"stop":195.901,"duration":16.78},{"text":"The white areas on this map are allotted Indian lands.","start":195.901,"stop":201.674,"duration":5.77},{"text":"The park outline in red is where the particular cigarette sales of Mr. Tonasket take place.","start":201.674,"stop":207.778,"duration":6.1},{"text":"Green are tribal lands both white and green are therefore restricted in the terms that have been used here for the last two days.","start":207.778,"stop":216.857,"duration":9.08},{"text":"The yellow lands are those lands on this part of the Indian reservation only, which have been patented and which are therefore subject to taxation.","start":216.857,"stop":227.4,"duration":10.54},{"text":"Most of which have probably been sold to non-Indians, but even if they are still retained by Indians, those yellows lands on the reservation do not support the peculiar claims for their owners, which the appellant makes here for his land.","start":227.4,"stop":245.132,"duration":17.73},{"text":"Which is still restricted as far as alienation and taxation is concerned.","start":245.132,"stop":249.629,"duration":4.5},{"text":"This portion, which is the upper part of this Section (a), is in the City of Omak.","start":249.629,"stop":256.594,"duration":6.97},{"text":"Some tribal land, some allotted land, a larger amount of patented land.","start":256.594,"stop":262.454,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How many cities?","start":262.454,"stop":263.639,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Just over 4000 people and it is the largest city on the reservation -- the City of Okanogan, which is the county city has about half that number.","start":263.639,"stop":272.907,"duration":9.27},{"text":"There are several other incorporated towns on or immediately adjacent to that reservation.","start":272.907,"stop":279.176,"duration":6.27},{"text":"It’s not until you get to the amicus tribes that you get to the extremely large cities of the State of Washington or their immediate area.","start":279.176,"stop":287.969,"duration":8.79}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The yellow section doesn’t concern us here then?","start":287.969,"stop":291.49,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"The only section does not concern you here.","start":291.49,"stop":293.246,"duration":1.76},{"text":"This is just that if we’re off the reservation.","start":293.246,"stop":295.923,"duration":2.68},{"text":"The point, Mr. Justice Douglas is that on reservations in the State of Washington not just the Colville reservation.","start":295.923,"stop":303.247,"duration":7.32},{"text":"This is a very typical pattern.","start":303.247,"stop":305.441,"duration":2.19},{"text":"We’re not dealing with the situation the Navajos described yesterday where Indian country is simply [Voice Overlap]","start":305.441,"stop":310.032,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"This – that is tough for the jury, I think because I happen to know that some reservation in Washington is not true.","start":310.032,"stop":316.593,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"There are maybe a few of the (Inaudible).","start":316.593,"stop":319.101,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But this one is the Yakima and they don’t have any such --","start":319.101,"stop":321.878,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":321.878,"stop":322.002,"duration":0.12},{"text":"Yes, they do Mr. Justice Douglas.","start":322.002,"stop":323.892,"duration":1.89},{"text":"The City of Toppenish is entirely located within the exterior boundaries of the Yakima.","start":323.892,"stop":328.144,"duration":4.25}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Which are under lease in them -- the Indian tribal council?","start":328.144,"stop":330.903,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Patented land.","start":330.903,"stop":332.684,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What made the town a Toppenish but not the land around it?","start":332.684,"stop":335.272,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Much land on the Yakima Reservation has been patented.","start":335.272,"stop":338.122,"duration":2.85},{"text":"Not the upper parts of the reservation in the rural areas.","start":338.122,"stop":340.876,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Just for the big California canners have their big crust of land.","start":340.876,"stop":343.766,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Where the -- where Wapato and Toppenish of that area is mostly patented land.","start":343.766,"stop":349.789,"duration":6.02},{"text":"Though, again there is a mixture as there is here.","start":349.789,"stop":351.909,"duration":2.12},{"text":"There’s land retained by Indians even down there.","start":351.909,"stop":357.399,"duration":5.49},{"text":"Moreover, there’s one other point, far from all of the Indians on the Colville -- in the Colville tribe live on the reservation.","start":357.399,"stop":365.797,"duration":8.4},{"text":"The record in this case indicates that between half and three quarters of them leave off the reservation add to that number, those Indians living on patented lands on the reservation and it’s clear that the extraordinary privileges claimed by appellant are likely to be available only to a capriciously fortunate minority of Colville or other Indians.","start":365.797,"stop":391.342,"duration":25.54},{"text":"And it’s this integration in these reservations, which gives rise to the importance of this case.","start":391.342,"stop":398.601,"duration":7.26},{"text":"Indeed, I think to its very existence and presence before you.","start":398.601,"stop":403.403,"duration":4.8},{"text":"It’s this integration, I believe, which accounts for the fact that until a last-ditch effort to show up appellant’s claim to tax exemption last spring.","start":403.403,"stop":414.136,"duration":10.73},{"text":"The Federal Indian Trader Act was simply unused in the State of Washington except on two isolated coastal reservations.","start":414.136,"stop":422.23,"duration":8.09},{"text":"They were all together.","start":422.23,"stop":423.472,"duration":1.24},{"text":"They shop in the same store as whether they were Indian or non-Indians.","start":423.472,"stop":428.189,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Now, the approach of Congress to Indian tax exemptions has been to set out post exemptions explicitly by statute.","start":428.189,"stop":437.051,"duration":8.86},{"text":"Mr. Cohen’s Treaties are written for that Bureau of Indian Affairs, which was quoted here yesterday.","start":437.051,"stop":442.295,"duration":5.24},{"text":"It says, “Indeed, such exemptions as apply to specific federal or state taxes on the income of Indians or on their property must be found then or derived from statutes and treaties or agreements with the Indian tribes.”","start":442.295,"stop":459.111,"duration":16.82},{"text":"The approach of this Court for many years has been identical.","start":459.111,"stop":463.337,"duration":4.23},{"text":"It has based successful exemption claims only on specific acts of Congress and not since the demise of implied governmental immunity 34 years ago in the Helvering case on general philosophical concepts.","start":463.337,"stop":479.382,"duration":16.05},{"text":"Now, appellants first and chief claim to a statutory exemption is based on the Indian Trader Act and this Court’s decision in Warren Trading Post.","start":479.382,"stop":490.734,"duration":11.35},{"text":"The exemption, which this Court found there was limited specifically and cautiously and by its expressed terms to sales by a license Indian trader to Indians, a class of sales of cigarettes which Washington statutes themselves exempt at the present time.","start":490.734,"stop":512.563,"duration":21.83},{"text":"The Indian Trader Act, the First Section of which is 25 U.S.C. 261 speaks directly of sales to Indians.","start":512.563,"stop":521.307,"duration":8.74},{"text":"In fact, should the sec -- should the Act be construed to apply to sales by Indians to non-Indians.","start":521.307,"stop":529.07,"duration":7.76},{"text":"Section 262 and 264 clearly require each non-Indian purchaser to obtain an Indian trader’s license, to go and buy these cigarettes.","start":529.07,"stop":539.62,"duration":10.55},{"text":"The absurdity of this result indicates the absurdity of appellant’s claim that he is exempted by the Indian Trader Act from a general non-discriminatory excise tax on his sales to non-Indians.","start":539.62,"stop":554.461,"duration":14.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"General Gorton, I understood the opinion of the -- of your state Court to all of the taxes applicable whether the sales were to Indians or non-Indians.","start":554.461,"stop":567.269,"duration":12.81}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"I will certainly get to that what I consider to be a philosophical point because we will claim that Warren Trading Post is not applicable to the State of Washington because of PL 83-280.","start":567.269,"stop":582.357,"duration":15.09},{"text":"The point I'm making now is that those cigarettes which we actually our attempting to tax.","start":582.357,"stop":588.306,"duration":5.95},{"text":"I think that exemption may have come into existence since the -- this since is rather -- this case has gone a long time since it came into existence.","start":588.306,"stop":596.518,"duration":8.21},{"text":"But the point that we’re arguing for here is solely the proposition of sales to non-Indians.","start":596.518,"stop":602.909,"duration":6.39},{"text":"We are not now trying to impose a cigarette tax on Indians.","start":602.909,"stop":607.543,"duration":4.63},{"text":"We would claim under PL 280 that we could if we wish, but we are not trying to do that now in this case.","start":607.543,"stop":614.406,"duration":6.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But your state court understood that the issue was involved sales to Indians or non-Indians?","start":614.406,"stop":622.516,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"I did not argue the case and the State Supreme Court.","start":622.516,"stop":625.123,"duration":2.61},{"text":"I think Mr. Pirtle statement yesterday was right that the distinction was made in the Supreme Court argument.","start":625.123,"stop":631.815,"duration":6.69},{"text":"It was not made by our State Supreme Court.","start":631.815,"stop":634.451,"duration":2.64},{"text":"In any event, it’s conscious of our state statutes in the exemption which they provide not just for sales by red license Indian Traders, but simply sales to non-Indians by any Indians tribe or through any Indian tribe.","start":634.451,"stop":649.816,"duration":15.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you thinking account on the Washington law passed February of this year?","start":649.816,"stop":655.891,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor I am.","start":655.891,"stop":658.602,"duration":2.71},{"text":"To the contrary of the position of even the Solicitor of much less the appellants, that Act doesn’t -- was designed to close the cigarette tax loopholes against Indians.","start":658.602,"stop":669.368,"duration":10.77},{"text":"The same legislature, which passed that statute, passed a conditional Appropriations Act of $8 million based on the usefulness of that Act in closing of these Indian cigarettes sales.","start":669.368,"stop":683.106,"duration":13.74},{"text":"In October this year for example, the loss to the state from Indian cigarettes sales of taxes alone was -- cigarette taxes alone was well over $600,000.","start":683.106,"stop":692.965,"duration":9.86},{"text":"That Act by its terms simply says that the state will no longer engage in useless Acts.","start":692.965,"stop":700.972,"duration":8.01},{"text":"This Court has recognized -- the Court has recognized that a state can’t collect an excise tax from the purchaser after he has made a purchase and distribute it himself to his home.","start":700.972,"stop":711.618,"duration":10.65},{"text":"An excise tax like this has got to be collected to the seller to be collected at all.","start":711.618,"stop":716.988,"duration":5.37},{"text":"There was an error in fact in the argument yesterday about competing cigarette taxes.","start":716.988,"stop":721.626,"duration":4.64},{"text":"Our tax is 16 cents, Oregon’s tax is 9 cents, Idaho’s tax is 9.1 cents, but this does mean that people will try to get away from taxes when they can.","start":721.626,"stop":732.038,"duration":10.41},{"text":"That’s why these people are selling cigarettes.","start":732.038,"stop":734.698,"duration":2.66},{"text":"What this --","start":734.698,"stop":734.972,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Are these separate law of this year as I understand, that allows sales to non-Indians of two cartons?","start":734.972,"stop":743.655,"duration":8.68}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, it does not.","start":743.655,"stop":745.433,"duration":1.78},{"text":"It allows the possession by any one for use of two cartons of cigarettes.","start":745.433,"stop":750.247,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What does the cigarette exempt?","start":750.247,"stop":751.544,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, it does not exempt any sale.","start":751.544,"stop":754.848,"duration":3.3},{"text":"It does not exempt any sale if there interpretation --","start":754.848,"stop":756.746,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the -- it releases the Indians from being the Indian seller from being a reporter or collector?","start":756.746,"stop":763.959,"duration":7.21}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"It does not Mr. Justice Douglas.","start":763.959,"stop":766.085,"duration":2.13},{"text":"It says, solely and only that the possession of two cartons of cigarettes at a time is not subject to a tax.","start":766.085,"stop":776.054,"duration":9.97},{"text":"It does not allow anyone to sell cigarettes even two cartons much less to posses 400 or 500.","start":776.054,"stop":783.054,"duration":7},{"text":"It is design solely to prevent the theoretical application to allot to someone who buys two cartons of cigarettes.","start":783.054,"stop":790.555,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"So the Solicitor General has misread the Act then?","start":790.555,"stop":792.972,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s -- the Act is clear.","start":792.972,"stop":794.983,"duration":2.01},{"text":"The Act -- that portion of the Act is absolutely clear that exemption applies only to possession and never to sale.","start":794.983,"stop":801.33,"duration":6.35},{"text":"Not to the sale of a single cigarette and it’s like many --","start":801.33,"stop":805.164,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Possession by the seller -- Indian seller?","start":805.164,"stop":807.881,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Possession by any purpose for purposes other than resale.","start":807.881,"stop":814.344,"duration":6.46},{"text":"This what the statute says, if acquired and possessed for purposes other than resale 400 or less cigarettes at any single time.","start":814.344,"stop":823.856,"duration":9.51},{"text":"Now, this appellant is out of that for two reasons.","start":823.856,"stop":826.861,"duration":3},{"text":"First, of course he obviously has more than 400 cigarettes at the time, and secondly, he holds them for resale.","start":826.861,"stop":833.356,"duration":6.5},{"text":"That’s what he’s doing, that’s with this case is all about.","start":833.356,"stop":837.813,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What is it in effect an exemption from a use tax that would otherwise [Voice Overlap]?","start":837.813,"stop":841.015,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"To the effect that the exemption from a use tax which we just couldn’t collect and which no state can collect.","start":841.015,"stop":847.325,"duration":6.31},{"text":"This kind of exemption I'm sure exists in many state excise tax statutes where you don’t -- it’s impractical to try to make a criminal out of the purchaser.","start":847.325,"stop":856.021,"duration":8.7},{"text":"You must collect these taxes from the seller or you can’t collect them at all.","start":856.021,"stop":863.17,"duration":7.15},{"text":"Now, appellant’s next claim to a statutory exemption from these particular excise taxes is based on Section 6 of the General Allotment Act is applied by this Court in Squire versus Capoeman.","start":863.17,"stop":877.252,"duration":14.08},{"text":"In that case, Chief Justice Warren stated that income from a timber sale from Mr. Capoeman’s allotment.","start":877.252,"stop":883.783,"duration":6.53},{"text":"The sale over which he had no control was exempt from the federal tax on capital gains.","start":883.783,"stop":890.143,"duration":6.36},{"text":"This Court found the sale to be the equivalent of a sale of the land itself.","start":890.143,"stop":895.336,"duration":5.19},{"text":"The finding was obviously correct and equally obviously inapplicable here.","start":895.336,"stop":900.933,"duration":5.6},{"text":"Timber can be cut from land such as Mr. Capoeman’s, literally once in a lifetime or less and the land that was found by the Court had little, if any additional value so that the proceeds of the timber sale constituted the only income in all probability, which the allotment would provide for Mr. Capoeman in his lifetime and amounted for his purposes were concern to a sale of the whole property.","start":900.933,"stop":927.26,"duration":26.33},{"text":"He had control over neither the fact nor the timing of the sale.","start":927.26,"stop":932.046,"duration":4.79},{"text":"Mr. Tonasket’s income here however is continuing.","start":932.046,"stop":936.132,"duration":4.09},{"text":"It is neither based on the fruits of the land nor on its exhaustion.","start":936.132,"stop":941.224,"duration":5.09},{"text":"It is simple business income.","start":941.224,"stop":944.477,"duration":3.25},{"text":"Moreover, Mr. Capoeman’s tax exemption had no adverse effects on timber sales by non-exempt landowners.","start":944.477,"stop":952.373,"duration":7.9},{"text":"Mr. Tonasket’s claim on the other hand, if upheld can and will destroy the businesses of competing sellers of cigarettes or of any other commodity, which Mr. Tonasket chooses to sell at retail.","start":952.373,"stop":966.676,"duration":14.3},{"text":"Finally, it seems doubtful that Mr. Tonasket’s inevitable claim to a federal income tax exemption on the profits of his sales is likely to have much appeal to this Court.","start":966.676,"stop":979.613,"duration":12.94},{"text":"Yet, it is the logical corollary of the extension of Squire versus Capoeman to a situation now before you, which was certainly not in the minds of the Court at the time that which that case was decided.","start":979.613,"stop":993.732,"duration":14.12},{"text":"Appellant’s final statutory claim to exemption is based on Section 4 of PL 83-280 itself.","start":993.732,"stop":1001.792,"duration":8.06},{"text":"A statute designed to authorize the extension of state jurisdiction over Indian reservations.","start":1001.792,"stop":1007.996,"duration":6.2},{"text":"The statute itself provides that it shall not “authorize the encumbrance or taxation of any real or personal property belonging to any Indian that is subject to a restriction against alienation imposed by the United States”.","start":1007.996,"stop":1024.887,"duration":16.89},{"text":"First of course, that statute doesn’t grant any tax exemption.","start":1024.887,"stop":1029.474,"duration":4.59},{"text":"It simply preserves those granted by other statutes from encroachment by the state.","start":1029.474,"stop":1035.595,"duration":6.12},{"text":"Moreover, it like all of those other statutes except perhaps the Indian Trader Act deals solely with property taxation.","start":1035.595,"stop":1044.156,"duration":8.56},{"text":"Nothing can be more clear from the decisions this Court and for that matter practically every other court in the land then the distinction between property and non-property taxes.","start":1044.156,"stop":1055.581,"duration":11.42},{"text":"This Court in U.S. v. Detroit even allowed the taxation on the leasehold interest on federal lands leased to private persons.","start":1055.581,"stop":1066.307,"duration":10.73},{"text":"The cigarette taxes and the sales taxes here in question are in no way property taxes.","start":1066.307,"stop":1073.419,"duration":7.11},{"text":"In addition, these excise taxes have two distinguishing features not shared by inheritance taxes involved in the Oklahoma cases or for that matter even by net income taxes.","start":1073.419,"stop":1084.816,"duration":11.4},{"text":"First of course, the ultimate burden of these taxes does not normally rest on the business charge with paying or collecting them.","start":1084.816,"stop":1093.396,"duration":8.58},{"text":"They are passed on to the ultimate purchaser of the cigarettes or other items offered for sale by the retailer.","start":1093.396,"stop":1100.677,"duration":7.28},{"text":"In fact, Mr. Justice Rehnquist, Washington State law requires that the sales tax be passed on.","start":1100.677,"stop":1106.639,"duration":5.96},{"text":"It is not permitted to be absorbed by the retailer.","start":1106.639,"stop":1110.949,"duration":4.31},{"text":"Second of course, appellant’s claim involves the right to destroy all of his competition in the sale of cigarettes.","start":1110.949,"stop":1118.148,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Appellant asserts in his brief that the 3 cents tax by the Colville tribe on each pack if added to the state 16 cent tax will wipe out his ability to sell cigarettes.","start":1118.148,"stop":1131.504,"duration":13.36},{"text":"How many cigarettes then will a competitor in the City of Omak without appellant’s claim the exemptions sale subject to a 16-cent tax in competition with appellant’s 3 cents?","start":1131.504,"stop":1145.958,"duration":14.45},{"text":"For that matter, how many appliances can a non-Indian businessman in Omak sell on which he must charge of 5% sales tax in competition with appellant who claims the right to sell the same article free from taxes?","start":1145.958,"stop":1162.166,"duration":16.21},{"text":"For that matter, referring back to one of yesterday’s cases, can a similar businessman in Seattle sells cigarettes or appliances in competition with an Indian seller for whom that BIA acquires property in Seattle under the claim of right asserted here yesterday by the appellant in Skelera (ph).","start":1162.166,"stop":1183.97,"duration":21.8},{"text":"Please remember that this appellant is a citizen of the State of Washington entitled to the rights of every other citizen including police protection, schools, and every other state and local governmental service.","start":1183.97,"stop":1202.385,"duration":18.41},{"text":"Nor is this a theoretical entitlement.","start":1202.385,"stop":1205.888,"duration":3.5},{"text":"All state and local governmental services are actually extended to Indians by Washington State often that a per capital cost to the state in excess of that to the average of non-Indians.","start":1205.888,"stop":1219.502,"duration":13.61},{"text":"In point of fact, we can at least asked the rhetorical question whether Congress could consistent with the Equal Protection Clause of the Constitution require us first in 1924 to have all Indians as citizens and then say that they should pay no taxes at all and this arises in these cases not an income tax cases or inheritance tax cases, which affect only the state.","start":1219.502,"stop":1244.99,"duration":25.49},{"text":"But in this case which affects other citizens of the state and their ability to do business.","start":1244.99,"stop":1252.189,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Now, at this point except in passing, I haven’t mentioned PL 83-280 for what I consider to be good reason.","start":1252.189,"stop":1262.935,"duration":10.75},{"text":"I do not believe that it extended the jurisdiction of the state to impose cigarette sales taxes, cigarette taxes, and sales taxes in Colville reservation.","start":1262.935,"stop":1273.27,"duration":10.34},{"text":"Because the state already had that right, but if there is any doubt about that jurisdiction, it is surely dispelled by PL 83-280.","start":1273.27,"stop":1286.571,"duration":13.3},{"text":"And that statute is relevant in connection with the one point in this case and which the Solicitor General asserts the possession, sales of cigarettes to Indians which are tax-exempt under the doctrine of Warren Trading Post in the absence of PL 83-280.","start":1286.571,"stop":1304.846,"duration":18.28},{"text":"Now, appellant has labored long in this murky legislative history of PL 83-280 without I submit producing a shred of evidence that it was intended to bar these taxes.","start":1304.846,"stop":1317.486,"duration":12.64},{"text":"He asserts that the law does nothing more than to extend state court jurisdiction.","start":1317.486,"stop":1323.392,"duration":5.91},{"text":"The statute help --","start":1323.392,"stop":1324.362,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Bring Governor Evans’ veto message, isn’t it.","start":1324.362,"stop":1328.085,"duration":3.72},{"text":"It indicates that this law legitimatize uses the word individual possession of two cartons or less of other stomp cigarettes if held for personal use, thus legitimatizing to that extent non-Indian purchases from Indian seller?","start":1328.085,"stop":1345.286,"duration":17.2}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas, Governor Evans is a good personal friend of mine, but he is not a lawyer and he is clearly in error in that statement.","start":1345.286,"stop":1354.046,"duration":8.76},{"text":"That Indian cigarette tax statute is clear on its face and it just simply does not legitimize such sales and --","start":1354.046,"stop":1363.858,"duration":9.81}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well apparently, this is not as clear as to the Solicitor General as you indicate nor the Governor Evans?","start":1363.858,"stop":1369.555,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it is from reading that statute which is the place where one will normally go to determining its meaning.","start":1369.555,"stop":1376.214,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I’ve just been reading it that it says, that the Indians are exempt if they have a permit from the state?","start":1376.214,"stop":1391.359,"duration":15.14}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"To sell to Indians, Your Honor.","start":1391.359,"stop":1393.599,"duration":2.24},{"text":"If you will read the Titles 82, 24 and 28, this is what my answer was here.","start":1393.599,"stop":1398.334,"duration":4.74},{"text":"This has been a case.","start":1398.334,"stop":1399.224,"duration":0.89},{"text":"This was a case before 1972.","start":1399.224,"stop":1401.904,"duration":2.68},{"text":"The 1972 Statute did not extend any right to sell by Indians to Indians which didn’t previously exist in our statute.","start":1401.904,"stop":1411.958,"duration":10.05},{"text":"That was already there -- the 1972 Act added the provision in this particular respect not with the person, this is any person may acquire and to physically possess if acquired and declared and possessed for purposes other than resale “for purposes other than resale” 400 or less cigarettes in any single time without incurring tax liability and that was the only addition, which was made by the statute, which is relevant to this particular question.","start":1411.958,"stop":1444.251,"duration":32.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When was the statute passed?","start":1444.251,"stop":1445.824,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"In the 1972 Session of State Legislation.","start":1445.824,"stop":1447.751,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So this was after the decision of the Supreme Court?","start":1447.751,"stop":1451.769,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1451.769,"stop":1454.014,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you suppose that the Supreme Court would have any different view of this case, had there -- had it had the new statute before it?","start":1454.014,"stop":1460.077,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"No way, Your Honor.","start":1460.077,"stop":1461.423,"duration":1.35},{"text":"As I say, there’s other legislative history of this Act, which indicates that the legislature felt that it was closing an $8 million per loophole by passing this Act in imposing the cigarette tax on the -- at the moment the cigarettes came in to the state and before even arrived on an Indian reservation.","start":1461.423,"stop":1481.161,"duration":19.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But let’s assume – let’s assume that the Act was construable.","start":1481.161,"stop":1485.256,"duration":4.1},{"text":"You say it isn’t, let suppose that was construable to say that the Indians could sell some exempt sales and the Supreme Court of your state construed the Act that way.","start":1485.256,"stop":1500.065,"duration":14.81},{"text":"Would it [Voice Overlap]?","start":1500.065,"stop":1500.841,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be -- that would govern.","start":1500.841,"stop":1502.621,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that was -- so there would have been a quite a different result in this case or not?","start":1502.621,"stop":1507.425,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"If it had, it is if you’re correct that my position is that it is not construable that’s clear on its face, but this --","start":1507.425,"stop":1513.859,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Attorney General, you have one view of it, but -- the Solicitor General and others have a different view of it.","start":1513.859,"stop":1520.371,"duration":6.51},{"text":"Since your Supreme Court didn’t have it before it when it decided the case, why don’t we not send this back, vacate this judgment, send it back for reconsideration on light of the new statute?","start":1520.371,"stop":1532.719,"duration":12.35},{"text":"Let your Supreme Court after all has finally decide it.","start":1532.719,"stop":1536.126,"duration":3.41},{"text":"Then you won’t have to have this argument with the bench.","start":1536.126,"stop":1540.058,"duration":3.93},{"text":"[Laughter] If you’re so correct.","start":1540.058,"stop":1543.46,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we have --","start":1543.46,"stop":1544.458,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Governor Evans is surrounded by very talented lawyers, he doesn’t write these things in vacuole?","start":1544.458,"stop":1554.229,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"You’re asking me to testify in this particular case, Your Honor [Laughter].","start":1554.229,"stop":1557.809,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we’re just asking you to do what’s you’ve have been doing, argue it.","start":1557.809,"stop":1561.446,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1561.446,"stop":1562.042,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Well, not when you ask me what Governor Evans was advised Your Honor.","start":1562.042,"stop":1565.219,"duration":3.18},{"text":"[Laughter] My point in this particular case though, is that that is essentially a useless Act.","start":1565.219,"stop":1573.335,"duration":8.12},{"text":"You have this case in all of its panoply before you.","start":1573.335,"stop":1579.257,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s what Mr. (Inaudible) has used.","start":1579.257,"stop":1581.15,"duration":1.89},{"text":"To send it back would be useless?","start":1581.15,"stop":1583.041,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because you will get an inevitable answer, Your Honor.","start":1583.041,"stop":1585.758,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you sure that Your Supreme Court’s going to construe the statute to a new view?","start":1585.758,"stop":1590.209,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Edit the state taxing statute.","start":1590.209,"stop":1592.69,"duration":2.48},{"text":"Now, if you feel in an excess of caution that you wish to do that, you nonetheless have the right and I believe this is the right time to construe [Voice Overlap].","start":1592.69,"stop":1601.405,"duration":8.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why should we decide a federal question if this case goes away, if your Supreme Court construes your new statute, contrary to the way you look at it?","start":1601.405,"stop":1612.126,"duration":10.72}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose my answer to that has to be that you are at least as capable of reading a statute as our State Supreme Court is and when we [Voice Overlap].","start":1612.126,"stop":1620.135,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We may be as capable but their view of the statute is what governs us.","start":1620.135,"stop":1625.438,"duration":5.3},{"text":"We can’t construe it for ourselves.","start":1625.438,"stop":1629.018,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you have two other cases here in front of you which involved at least some of the same questions except for the effect of PL 83-280.","start":1629.018,"stop":1637.917,"duration":8.9},{"text":"You were asked yesterday by appellant to send that back to our Supreme Court to determine whether it was correctly passed.","start":1637.917,"stop":1644.506,"duration":6.59},{"text":"Our Supreme Court already ruled on that, so as our Federal District Court, so as our Ninth Circuit Court.","start":1644.506,"stop":1649.227,"duration":4.72},{"text":"That too would be frivolous act.","start":1649.227,"stop":1650.61,"duration":1.38},{"text":"Those cases are already in our –- cited in our briefs.","start":1650.61,"stop":1656.78,"duration":6.17},{"text":"We have a case here on federal law, on federal questions, which is right then which is before you. On those federal questions and under which you don’t need to get to this.","start":1656.78,"stop":1667.012,"duration":10.23},{"text":"This man by his complaint is engaged in this resale of cigarettes.","start":1667.012,"stop":1672.797,"duration":5.79},{"text":"That’s a plain term, that’s what his business is -- the resale of cigarettes.","start":1672.797,"stop":1678.244,"duration":5.45},{"text":"Forever, [Voice Overlap].","start":1678.244,"stop":1678.288,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And of course you would say -- you would say it.","start":1678.288,"stop":1679.939,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Now, let’s assume you agreed for the moment that the statute was ambiguous.","start":1679.939,"stop":1684.89,"duration":4.95},{"text":"Would you suggest then that we send it back or not?","start":1684.89,"stop":1687.576,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"If the state statute is ambiguous and if it controls your decision in the case, you would have to.","start":1687.576,"stop":1693.268,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So, it’s just of really comes down to a matter whether we agree with you that the statute is so clear on its face that any arguments that -- has to its meaning contrary to yours is frivolous?","start":1693.268,"stop":1705.112,"duration":11.84}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that that is essential in the case, Your Honor.","start":1705.112,"stop":1707.444,"duration":2.33},{"text":"As long as you decide that this case would be governed by a state statute even if that we’re construed the other way.","start":1707.444,"stop":1714.313,"duration":6.87},{"text":"What if it was construed to allow someone to possess and resale two cartons of cigarettes, which is all they claim for.","start":1714.313,"stop":1722.39,"duration":8.08},{"text":"Still we’re not dealing with a person here who buys and resale two cartons of cigarettes.","start":1722.39,"stop":1727.84,"duration":5.45},{"text":"This is a big business.","start":1727.84,"stop":1727.965,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So you say that whatever the construction of the 72 Act whichever way it’s construed it wouldn’t control the outcome of this particular case?","start":1727.965,"stop":1735.023,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"It will not help Mr. Tonasket who is not a purchaser and seller of two cartons of cigarettes under any set of circumstances.","start":1735.023,"stop":1742.881,"duration":7.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Just awhile ago, I thought you said that it would made quite a difference if the statute have been before your State Supreme Court and the State Supreme Court took up the same view of the statute -- took a view of statute contrary to yours.","start":1742.881,"stop":1754.066,"duration":11.18}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are many ways to I which they can take a contrary to mine, Your Honor.","start":1754.066,"stop":1758.734,"duration":4.67},{"text":"They could say that a person may sell two cartons of cigarettes in an isolated sale without being subject to the statute.","start":1758.734,"stop":1766.693,"duration":7.96},{"text":"That would be contrary to my view, but that wouldn’t help Mr. Tonasket.","start":1766.693,"stop":1770.792,"duration":4.1},{"text":"He is a commercial seller of cigarettes.","start":1770.792,"stop":1774.193,"duration":3.4},{"text":"He doesn’t buy two cartons of cigarettes and sell them to a particular friend and then go buy two more and sell them to a friend.","start":1774.193,"stop":1781.21,"duration":7.02},{"text":"He is engaged in a commercial enterprise in competition with those --","start":1781.21,"stop":1784.296,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I know, but I thought the Solicitor General construed the statute to mean that a seller could sell two cartons to anyone person at anyone time?","start":1784.296,"stop":1794.515,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"The Solicitor General did, but the Solicitor General I will submit in this particular case totally misconstrued if the [Voice Overlap].","start":1794.515,"stop":1802.013,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know.","start":1802.013,"stop":1802.727,"duration":0.71},{"text":"Now, we’re back to the same old thing.","start":1802.727,"stop":1804.008,"duration":1.28},{"text":"How about your Governor, he construed at the same way, didn’t he?","start":1804.008,"stop":1806.593,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he did not.","start":1806.593,"stop":1807.99,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He didn’t?","start":1807.99,"stop":1808.105,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless, you can say for his construction was the one that we’ve -- I discussed here with Mr. Justice Rehnquist.","start":1808.105,"stop":1816.446,"duration":8.34},{"text":"We have, yes and excuse me, the sales tax issue is still here with you.","start":1816.446,"stop":1824.107,"duration":7.66},{"text":"The fact that the sales taxes applicable to these sales and that this particular claimant, claims the right to sell this article and other articles free from the state sales tax, which includes no such exemption in it.","start":1824.107,"stop":1837.501,"duration":13.39},{"text":"So, in any event, you have that matter before you.","start":1837.501,"stop":1841.306,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say -- when argued that this case is governed by the federal statute and what we can really lay aside the state statute, were you addressing yourself to the said part of Section 280 that provides that the state has jurisdiction over everything that applies to all other people in the State of Washington?","start":1841.306,"stop":1870.353,"duration":29.05}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor, I was and it was in that connection that this so-called new legislative history was brought up and sent to us about 10 days ago.","start":1870.353,"stop":1879.374,"duration":9.02},{"text":"And we on Monday, found something in the file, which we’re not supplied by the Solicitor General.","start":1879.374,"stop":1886.406,"duration":7.03},{"text":"A letter from the Assistant Secretary to the Interior to the House Committee, the Original Bill in 1953 HR10-63 included only the language on jurisdiction over civil causes of action in this particular respect.","start":1886.406,"stop":1904.146,"duration":17.74},{"text":"The Secretary suggested the language in which the Bill actually passed and said this that it was to extend to those reservations the substantive civil laws of the state in so far, as these laws are of general application to private persons or private property.","start":1904.146,"stop":1922.155,"duration":18.01},{"text":"Anyone on the call for the preservation on Indian law were not inconsistent with applicable state laws to assure “the predominance of state authority”.","start":1922.155,"stop":1934.277,"duration":12.12},{"text":"Now, can anyone seriously assert that the state excise tax laws are not substantive civil laws of general application?","start":1934.277,"stop":1943.415,"duration":9.14},{"text":"To state that question is simply to answer it.","start":1943.415,"stop":1947.4,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words when they seek to have all the benefits of citizenship and the protection of the substantive law then they take with that the burden a tax except as Congress or the state expressly exempts?","start":1947.4,"stop":1964.096,"duration":16.7}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely and that is what Congress did Mr. Chief Justice in PL-280.","start":1964.096,"stop":1970.709,"duration":6.61},{"text":"It accepted the property taxes on allotted lands, it accepted to a certain extent Indian laws where they want inconsistent with state law.","start":1970.709,"stop":1980.982,"duration":10.27},{"text":"That’s why it was not a Termination Act.","start":1980.982,"stop":1983.262,"duration":2.28},{"text":"The same Congress passed a group of termination acts.","start":1983.262,"stop":1986.253,"duration":2.99},{"text":"They wiped out the Indian tribes as entities.","start":1986.253,"stop":1991.315,"duration":5.06},{"text":"The existence of their reservations and property tax exemptions, this was not a Termination Act, but it was an Act which says that except where we have said specifically to the contrary, the state has all jurisdictions.","start":1991.315,"stop":2006.65,"duration":15.34},{"text":"You just can’t get any clearer, actually it’s a --","start":2006.65,"stop":2009.203,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But what about income tax on farm income from allotted lands after that 280?","start":2009.203,"stop":2018.558,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be an extension I think, not as great in the extension as this Squire versus Capoeman. Capoeman, I believe went off on the proposition, that you got this income only once in your lifetime?","start":2018.558,"stop":2030.793,"duration":12.23},{"text":"Effectively cutting timber was not like farming.","start":2030.793,"stop":2033.63,"duration":2.84},{"text":"Farming was -- [Voice Overlap]","start":2033.63,"stop":2034.95,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But arguably Squire would govern that?","start":2034.95,"stop":2037.043,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"Arguably, Squire would govern that case, but Squire certainly doesn’t govern this case.","start":2037.043,"stop":2042.304,"duration":5.26},{"text":"This isn’t income from land.","start":2042.304,"stop":2044.587,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s from transactions.","start":2044.587,"stop":2045.888,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Slade Gorton","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s from transactions.","start":2045.888,"stop":2047.647,"duration":1.76},{"text":"There’s no way that these taxes can be construed to be property taxes.","start":2047.647,"stop":2052.993,"duration":5.35},{"text":"It is simply aren’t property taxes in any respect whatsoever and it is only property taxes or taxes which have construed to be property taxes of which this Court has ever exempted in the Indian farms except in Warren Trading which itself was based on a specific statute.","start":2052.993,"stop":2073.695,"duration":20.7}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Attorney General.","start":2073.695,"stop":2077.429,"duration":3.73},{"text":"Mr. Pirtle, we will enlarge your time little bit because we have gone over with a lot of questions.","start":2077.429,"stop":2082.317,"duration":4.89},{"text":"So, you may proceed.","start":2082.317,"stop":2087.841,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":2087.841,"stop":2090.223,"duration":2.38},{"text":"There were -- there are several points that do need answering here and I would take them in order.","start":2090.223,"stop":2094.873,"duration":4.65},{"text":"First, I am not surprised that the Attorney General came up finally with the bootstrap argument.","start":2094.873,"stop":2099.951,"duration":5.08},{"text":"That argument is the state provides services therefore it should have the ability to tax.","start":2099.951,"stop":2105.867,"duration":5.92},{"text":"That’s a normative argument.","start":2105.867,"stop":2107.301,"duration":1.43},{"text":"It has nothing to do with the statutory problem of acquiring jurisdiction for taxing.","start":2107.301,"stop":2111.383,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Then what does Section 280 mean when it says as to civil jurisdiction the states after they have gone under 280 will have jurisdiction over civil cases.","start":2111.383,"stop":2127.179,"duration":15.8},{"text":"And to the same extents and this is the general part to the same extent that such state has jurisdiction over other several causes of action and those civil laws of such state that are of general application to private in persons and property?","start":2127.179,"stop":2147.239,"duration":20.06}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"But Your Honor, the answer to that is twofold.","start":2147.239,"stop":2150.694,"duration":3.45},{"text":"First, the language in there is not language of plenary grant such as you find in the Termination Acts, Klamath and Menominee.","start":2150.694,"stop":2158.947,"duration":8.25},{"text":"It’s very concise and it’s restricted to private persons and private property.","start":2158.947,"stop":2164.182,"duration":5.23},{"text":"Now, when you get to the cases and you can find this on page 7.","start":2164.182,"stop":2167.833,"duration":3.65},{"text":"The cases are enumerated on the brief of NCAI.","start":2167.833,"stop":2170.659,"duration":2.83},{"text":"You’ll find that civil law and criminal law are not the entire body of law.","start":2170.659,"stop":2176.8,"duration":6.14},{"text":"There is an additional third class which is that law of the sort of interface between sovereignty and the citizen.","start":2176.8,"stop":2183.948,"duration":7.15},{"text":"The sovereignty of the state government or the federal government and the citizen mostly it comes up in connection with cases of administrative proceedings.","start":2183.948,"stop":2193.496,"duration":9.55},{"text":"But a tax power is a sovereign power.","start":2193.496,"stop":2197.586,"duration":4.09},{"text":"In this case, we’re discussing the conflict between tribal tax power and state tax power.","start":2197.586,"stop":2202.755,"duration":5.17},{"text":"That is not a law of governing private persons and private property to use that narrow language.","start":2202.755,"stop":2208.742,"duration":5.99},{"text":"And the Attorney General failed to read to you from the last sentence in that letter from Ormie Louis which by the language with the published reports.","start":2208.742,"stop":2216.74,"duration":8},{"text":"So, it’s nothing new.","start":2216.74,"stop":2218.365,"duration":1.63},{"text":"He said, but with he said, this should make the state laws apply and to civil transactions among Indians.","start":2218.365,"stop":2227.836,"duration":9.47},{"text":"Taxing power by either state or the tribe is not a civil transaction.","start":2227.836,"stop":2232.126,"duration":4.29},{"text":"That clearly is outside the meaning of that narrow language and then he goes on to say, but with a minimum of interference with Indian control of Indian affairs.","start":2232.126,"stop":2242.267,"duration":10.14},{"text":"Now, the Court might say to itself that language is rather broad perhaps, it’s overly broad if the Court feels it’s overly broad, the Court can restrict it.","start":2242.267,"stop":2253.442,"duration":11.18},{"text":"And I suggest that the Court should restrict in accordance with the Court’s rule in the Holy Church case in which the church in New York imported a vicar from England for its preacher.","start":2253.442,"stop":2267.154,"duration":13.71},{"text":"And they clearly violated a federal statute they said, you shall not import people from outside the country to take jobs for you.","start":2267.154,"stop":2274.225,"duration":7.07},{"text":"And this Court said, when language can be extended beyond the meaning of the legislature, it must be restricted to the intent of the legislature.","start":2274.225,"stop":2281.999,"duration":7.77},{"text":"When it says as specifically, here we don’t even have it specifically.","start":2281.999,"stop":2285.587,"duration":3.59},{"text":"We have just broad language of civil law as true, but then it’s narrowed by those modifiers to private persons and private property.","start":2285.587,"stop":2295.512,"duration":9.93}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But you’ve indicated that perhaps, there might be some ambiguity in 280 in the passage that are I was reading.","start":2295.512,"stop":2302.665,"duration":7.15},{"text":"But the Committee Report on that after some preliminaries about the efforts to draw all Indians into the total culture goes on to say that it extends to those reservations the substantive civil laws of the respective States.","start":2302.665,"stop":2327.379,"duration":24.71},{"text":"Now, do you say that substantive civil laws do not include the tax statutes?","start":2327.379,"stop":2332.339,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor you have to read that in context.","start":2332.339,"stop":2334.182,"duration":1.84},{"text":"It says substantive civil laws of the States and it goes on to talk about civil transactions among Indians.","start":2334.182,"stop":2339.23,"duration":5.05}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I want to read the rest of the sentence.","start":2339.23,"stop":2341.955,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Substantive civil laws of the respective States in so far as those laws are general application to the private persons or private property?","start":2341.955,"stop":2351.006,"duration":9.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2351.006,"stop":2351.805,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But now, isn’t the tax on sales?","start":2351.805,"stop":2356.815,"duration":5.01},{"text":"Doesn’t that have something to do with private persons and private property?","start":2356.815,"stop":2360.302,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"I think not.","start":2360.302,"stop":2362.559,"duration":2.26},{"text":"I would say that that has to do with the sovereign ability of a state to tax.","start":2362.559,"stop":2367.579,"duration":5.02},{"text":"The tax may fall on many areas of private property, transactions, excise, etcetera.","start":2367.579,"stop":2374.274,"duration":6.69},{"text":"But I think that that language when you look at the entire statute, look at the entire legislative history, there’s no tax talk specifically tax talk except on that discussion in the sub-committee hearing.","start":2374.274,"stop":2385.882,"duration":11.61},{"text":"And there it’s made very clear that Congress does not intend to any tax to be levied from the Indian people.","start":2385.882,"stop":2391.804,"duration":5.92},{"text":"It was never discussed and clearly, the Congress first purpose in the 1968 Act would be frustrated if they were eluding on of state taxes prior to the consent by the Indian people to jurisdiction.","start":2391.804,"stop":2408.368,"duration":16.56},{"text":"Now, I answer one additional argument Your Honors and that is -- this is the bootstrap argument.","start":2408.368,"stop":2414.855,"duration":6.49},{"text":"The argument that the state provides services and therefore they should have the power to tax.","start":2414.855,"stop":2419.674,"duration":4.82},{"text":"Now, --","start":2419.674,"stop":2419.971,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Section 2 (b) and 4 (b) as I read them cited that this Section which is the at new law 280 shall -- nothing in this Section shall authorize the taxation of any real or personal property of any Indian or Indian tribe.","start":2419.971,"stop":2444.496,"duration":24.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s true Your Honor and it also says, or regulation of the use of such property inconsistent with federal policies and statutes.","start":2444.496,"stop":2453.571,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But does that do any more than preserve the exemptions which Congress had already explicitly extended to Indian lands?","start":2453.571,"stop":2462.678,"duration":9.11},{"text":"It’s a Saving Clause, isn’t it?","start":2462.678,"stop":2464.41,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it is Your Honor, but there are two points to be made here.","start":2464.41,"stop":2467.675,"duration":3.27},{"text":"One is that the language of encumbrance -- this Court found on the Squire case to include also the federal income tax of problem.","start":2467.675,"stop":2477.45,"duration":9.77},{"text":"And this Court ruled in the Rickert case that the General Allotment Act which required that there be no, at the end of the trust period, there’ll be no lien, there’ll be no prior debt which could attach to the property said.","start":2477.45,"stop":2491.387,"duration":13.94},{"text":"That language in extends not only to the land, but to the horse, the plow and the barns on that building.","start":2491.387,"stop":2499.266,"duration":7.88},{"text":"That’s the personal property needed to use the land.","start":2499.266,"stop":2502.509,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s what went way off from cigarettes, cartons of cigarettes, isn’t it?","start":2502.509,"stop":2505.885,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"I think not Your Honor, because it take -- compare Mr. Tonasket with Squire.","start":2505.885,"stop":2510.361,"duration":4.48},{"text":"Squire was lucky enough, fortunate enough not to have growing timber on his land.","start":2510.361,"stop":2514.152,"duration":3.79},{"text":"Mr. Tonasket has nothing but grass.","start":2514.152,"stop":2516.824,"duration":2.67},{"text":"Now, the Congress -- the purpose of Congress today is in the promulgating the Tobacco Ordinance of the Colville tribe for example is clearly that trust land be utilized in a modern way.","start":2516.824,"stop":2530.193,"duration":13.37},{"text":"It is no part in expecting the Indian the poor Indian to be a farmer on his land in East Omak which is an Indian village.","start":2530.193,"stop":2537.444,"duration":7.25},{"text":"When he has no timber on it and when the only really legitimate and sensible method of developing the land is some kind of a commercial enterprise.","start":2537.444,"stop":2548.113,"duration":10.67},{"text":"Now, I would say additionally, Your Honors, that in the Kansas Indians case, this Court said specifically that conferring rights and privileges on the Indians cannot affect their situation which can only be changed by treaty stipulation or voluntary abandonment of their tribe and organization.","start":2548.113,"stop":2566.005,"duration":17.89},{"text":"In the case which the Attorney General cited in his opinion as direct President Goody versus Smith, the Court the quotations there are from the In re. Heff case.","start":2566.005,"stop":2578.099,"duration":12.09},{"text":"Those are the ones in which the Court had earlier said Mr. Justice Rutledge and in a not very well thought out opinion that the General Allotment Act which conferred citizenship and the right to vote and participate in Government also made people subject to taxation and this Court specifically overruled Heff in United States versus Nice in 1916.","start":2578.099,"stop":2599.737,"duration":21.64},{"text":"So, the very foundation of the Goody versus Smith case has been overruled by this Court.","start":2599.737,"stop":2606.604,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I think your time is up now counsel.","start":2606.604,"stop":2607.787,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Pirtle","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":2607.787,"stop":2609.133,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you gentlemen.","start":2609.133,"stop":2609.822,"duration":0.69},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2609.822,"stop":2611.984,"duration":2.16}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Dec  12 - 13, 1972","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"71-1031","citation":"411 US 451 (1973)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/411/451","lowerCourt":"Washington Supreme Court","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Apr 24, 1973"}